{"/service/ndnp/mnhi/batch_mnhi_katherine_ver01/data/sn89064422/00542865556/1929112201/0358.xml":{"full_text":">AY, NOVEMBER 22, 1929\nCWS SE\u00a3S UNEM\nPLOYMENT COMING\nBy Laurence Todd\nFederated Frees\nWASHINGTON\u2014(FP)\u2014Sen. Cou\nzens of Michigan, formerly partner of\nHenry Ford, believes that business\nconditions are getting so bad that\ngreat unemployment may be expect\ned during the coming winter. He has\nmade public a letter he addressed to\nthe Detroit Community Chest, for\nwarding SIOO,OOO as his contribution\nto the burden the charities in the\nmotor car production center must\nbear in the next few months.\n\u201cBecause of the growing unemploy\nment,\u201d Couzens wrote, \u201cI am concern\ned about the distress that these un\nemployed will suffer during the com\ning winter. With this subscription I\nexpress the hope that not only my\nsubscription but all possible subscrip\ntions may be used by those agencies\ndealing with medical, child\nren's and family relief in particular\nwhile unemployment conditions pre\nvail.\u201d\nCouzens has learned that Detroit is\ndiscussing the setting up of a special\nindustrial commission of city officials\nand business men to distribute jobs\n\u201cequitably\u201d and to promote the doing\nof public work and building construc\ntion new as an emergency of giving\nwork to the unemployed.\nPresident Hoover has thus far\nmade no statement on the growth of\nthe army of jobless. He has, howev\ner, a nationwide information through\nthe employment offices of the De\npartmentof Labor and the reports\nreceived by the Bureau of Labor sta\ntistics, the Federal Reserve Board\nand the Bureau of Foreign and Do\nmestic Commerce, which enables hun\nto watch the industrial barometer.\nSince one of the boasts of his admin\nistration has been the wide distribu\ntion of stock ownership among the\nAmerican people, Hoover is keenly\nconscious of the feeling of poverty\nwhich has oppressed millions of in\ndividuals since the \u201cHoover market\u201d\ncrashed and the inflated valuations of\nstocks were reduced by more than\nthirty billion dollars.\nSecretary Mellon is now trying to\nexplain away his stock-boosting\nstatements to press correspondents\nduring the weeks just preceding the\ncollapse. The fact remains that the\nstock speculators, among whom were\nmany thousands of families whose\nsavings were gambled away in the\nfever of marginal trading, knew that\nHoover and Mellon were steadily en\ncouraging the public to believe that\nthe stock market quotations repre\nsented real values, immediate or as\nsured.\nPeople who have lest heavily in\nthis panic will be unable to spend\nmuch money during the Christmas\nseason. Prices of luxury goods are\nalready being slashed as the prospec\ntive market shrinks. Manufacturers\nof luxury goods of every kind are\ngrowing cautious. Ihis means a re\nduction in employment all over the\nindustrial map. Confidence in a\nprompt return of \u201cprosperity\u201d would\nsave the jobs of hundreds of thous\nands of breadwinners in the next 60\ndays. But the Hoover administration\ndoes not, apparently possess the\npower of restoring that confidence.\nThe theory that Hoover had dis\ncovered the golden secret of \u201cestab\nilized prosperity\u201d has suffered a mor\ntal blow.\nCLASSIFIED\nWANT ADS\nWANTED \u2014Feed to grind every\nMonday. Starting Nov. 25. Alfred\nMuhlman, Hay Creek. (26-27-p)\nFOR SALE\u2014Stott Briquets \u201cThe\nPerfect Fuel\u201d. Call Wm. Scherf,\nFrontenac. (25-tf)\nFOR SALE \u2014Ideal Confectionery\nincluding building at 1522 Main St.\nCall at place of business. (26-28)\nFOR SALE \u2014White Minorca, White\nRock, White Wyandotte cockrels, $2\neach. Phone 27-F-23. Call during\nnoon hour. (26-28-p)\nGET YOL\u2019R Denatured Alcohol at\nH. M. Bird\u2019s, 217 Main Street. 60c\nper gallon. (22-29)\nWANTED \u2014Carpenter work. Work\nguaranteed. Chas. A. Nelson, Hast\nings, Minn. (23-34-p)\nFOR SALE \u2014Pure English leghorn\ncockerels, Tom Baron strain. Ed\nSprikes, Zumbrota, Rt. 2. 21-23-p\nGET YOUR Straw flowers and Bit\nter sweets at the Wacouta Store\nNOW. Makes beautiful winter bou\nquets.\nMONEY TO LOAN\u2014S 1-2 per cent\non Farm Mortgages.\u2014A. F. HERN\nLEM, 317 East Avenue, Red Wing,\nMinn. 11-31-29\nNOW IS THE TIME to buy Dr.\nHess Stock Tonic for your stock, and\nPan-a-min an egg producer for your\nchickens, for sale at Geo. C. Diercks,\nGoodhue, Minn. (26-29-p)\n\nFOR SAIJC-^^urebred Shorpshire\naged ram,.^r^4|l^- Pure bred reg\nistered Here^rd calves, 5 months\nand under JwEpjtey^^uhman. Goodhue\nMinn. -2\nU. S. MAY BUILD OWN\nFLATHEAD POWER PLANT\nWASHlNGTON\u2014Possibility\nthe government may build and oper\nate a hydro-electric plant on the Flat\nhead riverin Montana rather than\neither of the two applicants now ap\npearing before the federal power\ncommission was suggested today by\nAssistant Indian Commissioner Scat-\ntergood.\n\u201cThe government could develop\nthis plant and do everything these ap\nplicants propose to do and do it much\ncheaper,\u201d he said. \u201cIt would also take\nadequate care of the Indians and the\nwhite setllers on irrigated lands near\nby.\u201d\nDepartment of Commerce\nFinds Chain Stores Grow\nWASHINGTON \u2014The department\nof commerce has studied the passing\nof chain stores and independent re\ntail stores in a representative south\nern city of 60,000 population over a\nperiod of five years ended in 1928.\nThe independent stores had a mor\ntality rate of 55% while the chain\nstores\u2019 rates was but 17%.\nBUILDING WORK DROPS\nf Washington\u2014Official reports from\n596 leading cities and towns in every\npart of the United States show mark\ned decline in building permits, as\ncompared with September this year\nand the same month last year.\nMore Millionaires\nWASHINGTON\u2014The number of\nmillionaires in this country is increas\ning according to government income\nstatistics for 1927. The report shows\na total of 290 individual incomes of\nmore than $1,000,000 each.\n\u201cHey\u201d yelled the Sergeant at the\nrifle practice, \u201cdon\u2019t you know bette--\nthan to fire before the range is clear?\nYou just missed me.\u201d\n\u201cI\u2019m awfully sorry, Sergeant,\u201d re\nplied the recruit.\nLEGAL\nORDER\nState of Minnesota. County of Ccodhue,\nss. In District Court, First Judicial District.\nFarwell. Ozmun, Kirk\nCompany, a corporation. Plaintiff,\nvs.\nConPhuo County Co-operative\nCompany, a corporation. Defendant.\nOn reading and filirv the final r^pcrl and\nTceount of C. D. Maclaren and C. F. Hjerm\nstad, receivers in the above entitled matter\nand on motion of Messrs. Thomas Mohn and\nHorace W. Mohn, and Todd, Fosnes Green,\nattomevg for so\u2019d receivers.\nIT IS FEPEBY ORDERED, That said final\nreport and account be beard at the adjourned\ngeneral term of this Court to be held in the\nCourt House in the City of Red Wing, Good\nhue County, Minnesota, or. the 30th day of\nNovember. 1929, at 10 o\u2019clock A. M.. or as\nsoon thereafter as counsel can be heard, and\nthat notice of hearing on said report and ac\ncount be given by publishing a copy of this\norder once prior to said date in the Red Wing\nDaily Eagle. The Organized Farmer and the\nDailv Republican, all published in the City\nof Red Wing. Minnesota, and that a copy\nthereof be mailed to the last known post of\nfice address of each creditor whose claim has\nbeen filed and allowed in this proceeding,\nwhich said moiling shall be at least eight\ndavs before said day of hearing.\nIT IS FURTHER ORDERED. That the un\ncollected judgments, accounts receivable and\nunsold personal property referred to in said\nreport and account be offered for sale at\npublic auction at the time and place of the\nhearing on said report and account to the\nhighest bidder or bidders for cash therefor,\nsaid sales to be subject to confirmation of the\nCourt.\nThat at the time of said hearing, and upon\nadjournment thereof, if any, the Court will\nexamine the report and account of said re\nceivers, adjudicate the same and make his\nfinal order of allowance to the receivers and\ntheir attorneys, and for distribution of the\nresidue of the assets.\nDated at Red Wing, Minesota, this 19th\nday of November, 1929.\nCHAS. P. HALL\n(26) District Judge.\nCITATION FOR HEARING ON PETITION\nFOR ADMINISTRATION\nEstate of W. J. Warner, Deceased.\nState of Minnesota, County of Goodhue, in\nProbate Court.\nIn the Matter of the Estate of W. J. War\nner, Decedent.\nTHE STATE OF MINNESOTA TO ALL\nPERSONS INTERESTED IN THE ABOVE\nENTITLED MATTER: Whereas John D.\nWarner has filed in this Court a petition\npraying for administration of the estate of\nthe above named decedent and that letters\nof administration thereon be granted to C. W.\nBeckman.\nIT IS THEREFORE ORDERED. That said\npetition be heard, and that all persons inter\nested in said matter be and appear before\nthis Court' j\u00bbn the 2nd day of December, 1929,\n\u2022at 10 o\u2019clock A. M.. at the Probate Court\nRooms in the Court House, at Red Wing, in\nsaid County, and then and there, or as soon\nthereafter, as said matter can be heard, show\ncause, if any they have, why said petition\nshould not be granted, and that this citation\nbe served by the publication thereof in The\nOrganized Farmer, according to law.\nWitness the Honorable, Wm. M. Erickson,\nfudge of said Court, ani the seal of said\nCourt, this 18th day of October 1929\n(Court Seal) ALFRED G. REHDER\nClerk of Probate Court\nThos. Mohn and Horace W. Mohn,\nAttorneys Tor Petitioner. (22-25)\nCITATION FOR HEARING ON PETITION\nFOR ADMINISTRATION\nEstate of Michael Redding, deceased.\nState of Minnesota, County of Goodhue, in\nProbate Court.\nIn the Matter of the Estate of Michael Red\nding, Decedent.\nTHE STATE OF MINNESOTA TO Maria\nRedding, Wm. A. Redding, Edgar H. Red\nding, Louis M. Redding and all persons in\nterested in the above entitled matter Where\nas Maria Redding has filed in this Court a\npetition praying for administration of the\nestate of the above named decedent and that\nletters of administration thereon be granted\nto herself.\nIT IS THEREFORE ORDERED. That said\npetition be heard, and that all persons inter\nested in said matter be and appear before\nthis Court on the 9th day .of December 1929,\nat 10 o'clock A. M.. at the Probate Court\nRooms in the Court House, at Rod Wing,\nin said County, and then and there, or as\nsoon thereafter, as said matter can be heard,\nshow cause, if nay they have, why- a^d petit\nCe^KlU? tls\nCourt, thia 89th day of October 1929.\nCome Into My Parlor!\n7 Jp.. .-e n Drawn for LABOR by JohnlL Baer.\nKENYON\nLapsKauS\nMr. and Mrs. Norman Eide of Far\nibault and Oscar Eide of Kenyon were\nguests at the J. C. Eide home in\nHolden on Sunday.\nConfirmation services were held at\nthe Holden church cn Sunday Novem\nber 17. A class consisting of four\ngirls and- two boys were confirmed\nby the pastor, Rev. S. O. Simundson\nHazel Lee; Mildred Wickum, Leona\nLangemo, Julia Davidson, Olaf Jor\nstad and Herman Svee composed the\nclass.\nRev. C. A. Stormo and family were\nguests of honor at a housewarming\nparty, given by a large number of\nmembers of the First Lutheran\nchurch of Kenyon, who gathered at\nthe church basement recently to cele\nbrate the finishing of the new church\nparsonage which has just been com\npleted. Rev. Stormo and his family\nare now comfortably residing in the\nnewly built home. A bounteous buffet\nsupper was served by the ladies of\nthe aid society, who had brought all\nof the dishes with them for the occa\nsion.\nMr. John Mogren is improving his\nproperty in the northeast part of\ntown, by building a large dam on the\nZumbro river near the ice house.\nDr. and Mrs. Howard Strange and\nson, of Chicago, have been guests at\nthe Samuel Sands home for some\ntime.\nMiss Valborg Lelund, who is teach\ning in Fargo, North Dakota, this\nyear was here on a visit with her par\nents, Dr. and Mrs. Leland last week.\nOn Saturday evening of last week\na number of neighbors and friends of\nMrs. A. G. Flom, gathered at the\nhome of Mrs. Samuel Sande at a\nfarewell party in honor of Mrs. Flom\nwho is leaving Kenyon to reside with\nher daughters in Minneapolis and\nStillwater in the future.\nThe following teachers from this\nvicinity and the members of the local\nnormal training department of- our\nlocal school, attended the rural teach\ners convention at Red Wing the first\npart of this month: Miss Marie Dale,\nEffie Cordes, Bertha Danielson, Ida\nHalseth, Luella Luebke, Frances Val\nley, Ruth Bergum, Anna Tuve, Ber\nnice Haugen and Lorena Bowe.\nOn Saturday evening, November 9\nMr. and Mrs. Obert Haugen were\nvery pleasantly surprised on their\nfifth wedding anniversary, at the\nhome of Mr. and Mrs. Martin Flom.\nA substantial sum of money was pre\nsented to them by the large number\nof relatives and friends, who had ga\nthered to help them celebrate this\nhappy event. A delicious luncheon\nwas served and an enjoyable evening\nspent.\nPlans for the reunion of more than\n300 persons, former residents of Ken\nyon, living in St. Paul and Minneapol\nis which have been in charge of Mrs.\nR. E. Hilton and Mrs. Chas Lindholm\nof Minneapolis for some time took\nplace at the midway club, on Tues\nday, November 19th. Kenyon was set\ntled in 1851 by a group of New York\ners who went up the Mississippi rjver\nas far as Red Wing and then equip\nped with ox teams and prairie schon\ners headed west with a view- to set-\nU^nent ip the Dakotas, but at <^e end\nQf^e second day\u2019s they\ncam^ied oh the banks %mbro\nd\u00dfier, and liked it so -w|\\ihai they\nratted out claims ther^^U\nThe marriage of Mi^M^oi^Fly-\n\u25a0ehoMtl. and .T \u2018WjfcJmAinn\ncoach of athletics at the Luverne high\nschool, took place on Thursday, Oct.\n31. The newly weds will make their\nhome in Minneapolis. The many\nfriends of Miss Flygare here, wish\nher much happiness in her wedded\nlife.\nOn Thursday evening of last week,\nKenyon members of the Tyrian Chap\nter No. 6. R. A. M. of Faribault were\npresent at a 6:30 p. m. banquet, af\nter which they took part in the reg\nular work. Those from here, who at\ntended, were C. Clausen, Arthur\nPicha, L. Wenzel, Dr. E. Bache, Har\nry Bergh, Arthur Borlaug, O. C:\nCole, George Elcock and B. C. Stod\ndard.\nKnut Halvorson, pioneer settler of\nGoodhue county, passed away cn\nWednesday, October 30th. He was\nborn in Norway May 22, 1844. Imi\ngrated to America with his parents\nat the age of four, his parents set\ntling in Dane county, Wisconsin. Mr.\nHalvorsen died while crossing the\nocean. After finishing the common\nschool he entered Albion Academy,\ngraduating at the age of 15. He\ntaught parochial and public schools in\nWisconsin for four years. In 1866 he\ncame to Goodhue county, where he\ntaught school for eleven years near\nKenyon. In 1877 he settled on a farm\nwhere he lived until his death. On\nSeptember 25th, 1878 he was united\nin marriage to Caroline Gunhus of\nKenyon township by Rev. M. O.\nBoeckman. Ten children were born\nto them one of whom died in infan\ncy. He leaves to mourn his death,\nhis widow and three sons. Albert,\nCharles and George, six daughters,\nMrs. John Scott, Sheldon, lowa, Mrs.\nCarl Eiken, St. Paul; Mrs. Julius Er\nler, Mrs. Alfred Anderson, Mrs. A.\nStrandemo and Mrs. Ted Knutson of\nthis vicinity. Twenty grandchildren\nand four half sisters and four half\nbrothers. Funeral services were held\nSaturday, November 3 at the Moland\nchurch. Rev. Otto Jacobson officiat\ning. Solo numbers were rendered by\nR. B. Hanson, accompanied by Mrs.\nHanson of Kenyon. Pall bearers were\nOle Halvorson and Erick Dokken of\nKenyon, Julius Halvorson of Skyberg,\nMartin and Carl Dokken and Sever\nBrusletten of Gol. Those from a dis\ntance attending the funeral were:\nMr. and Mrs. Carl Eiken, St. Paul;\nMr. and Mrs. John Scott, Oliver\nErickson and Henry Erickson of\nSheldon; Edward Sanders, Forest\nLake; Mr. and Mrs. Eli Erickson and\nMr. and Mrs. Ben Hattland, Esther\nville, Iowa; Mr. and Mrs. L. Barr,\nEllington; Mr. and Mrs. Ole Halvor\nson, Mr. and Mrs. Martin Dokken,\nMr. and Mrs. Julius Halvorson, Mrs.\nGunder Gunhus; Mrs. C. Brusletten,\nMr. and Mrs. Carl Benson, Mrs. Paul\nHulebak, Carl Dokken, Miss Chris\ntin Doken, and Sever Brusletten all\nof Kenyon.\nRECOVERS FROM INJURIES\nHenning Anderson, who was pain\nfully injured when he fell from a tank\nwhile employed at the Pittsburgh\nPlate glass company plant, is now\nable to be up and around after being\nconfined to the hospital for several\nweeks. Mr. Anderson suffered a frac\ntured shoulder blade and received\nnumerous body bruises.\nSOCIETY TO GIVE PROGRAM\nThe Gleaner society of the Vasa\nLutheran church will present a pro\ngram and conduct a sale at the Vasa\ntown hall this evening at 8 o*clock.\nRefreshments Will be served fblow\nin^ the program and the pubiiels\ncordially invited. V-\nPlainview, Wis. Echoes\nMr. and Mrs. Barney Fluger vis\nited Thursday evening at the Barney\nDenzer home.\nHarris Pearson, who went to lowa\nto pick corn, returned last week. Em\nmett Myers and Lawrence Larson are\nstill on duty picking corn.\nRoy Olson who underwent an oper\nation at the St. John\u2019s hospital was\nreported getting along nicely.\nMrs. Alfred Anderson, who some\ntime ago underwent an operation, was\nbrought back to her home and is get\nting along fine.\nMr. and Mrs. Louis Larson enter\ntained company from Red Wing Sun\nday.\nAnna Clobes who has been working\nin Red Wing the past week spent\nSunday with her parents, Mr. and\nMrs. John Clobes and family.\nMr. and Mrs. John Winerich and\ndaughter, Joan, spent Sunday with\nher mother, Mrs. Anna Myers and\nbrother, Irvin.\nMr. and Mrs. John Knudson and\nfamily motored to the cities Sunday.\nMrs. Oscar Anderson and Mrs.\nArchie Anderson visited Thursday af\nternoon with Mrs. Anna Myers.\nThe Good Natured Community\nClub met Friday evening at the Plain\nview school and a fair sized crowd at\ntended.\nMiss Ethel Dahl visited Friday af\nternoon at the Fred Fynn home.\nArchie Dahl come home frotn St.\nPaul Saturday and spent Sunday\nwith home folks.\nMr. and Mrs. Albert Flynn visited\na week ago Friday evening at the\nMrs. Anna Myers home.\nCharles G. Anderson and son Elmer\nwere callers at the Myers home\nThursday evening.\nIt\u2019s easy to buy your Xmas gifts at\nthe Friendly Store. During their trav\nels our buyers have gathered an out\nstanding assortment of useful gifts.\nGamble Stores.\nFresh From The\nOvens To You\nSwiss Rolls 1 9\nper doz. v\nCream Puffs g\"-\nEach wv\nNapoleon Slices Ep\nEach v v\nPumpkin QAn\nPies each vUv\nCurrant Rolls OAa\nDoz. 4Vv\nLimpa Bread 1 An\nI lb. loaf XUC\nALLYN\u2019S\nBAKERY^\nPAGE FIVE\nHOOVER CALLS WOLVES IN\nPLAN TO STEAL THE ENTIRE\nWORLD DURING SLACKNESS\nBy Laurence Todd\nFederated Press\nWASHINGTON\u2014 (FP)\u2014 President\nHoover\u2019s invitation to the utilities in\ndustry to come into his conferences\non the business depression, along with\nthe railroads, manufacturers, bankers\nand agriculture, has given the power\ntrust new hope of getting hold of\nimportant properties belonging to the\npublic. Boulder Dam, the Flathead\nsite in Montana, and the remaining\npower at Niagra Falls are the immed\niate stakes in the game. After that\nwill come an attempt to get posses\nsion of the government power plant at\nMuscle Shoals.\nPublic ownership advocates, includ\ning the representative of the southern\nCalifornia cities who have been fight\ning to save the Boulder Dam power\nfor distribution among the municipal\nities of that region, are disturbed by\nthe emphasis placed by the White\nHouse on the job-giving possibilities\nof the power companies. This sounds\nto them Bke ah excuse for making\nan \u201cemergency\u201d award of 25 per cent\nof the Boulder Dam power to the\nSouthern California Edison Co., as\nproposed by Secretary WHlbur, oppon\nent of public ownership. It may serve\nas a pretext also for delivering the\nFlathead power site to the Electric\nBond Share Co., through the Mon\ntana Power Co. It may cover the\ndetermination of Secretary Bonner of\nthe Federal Power Commission to\ngive the last Niagra power to the Ni\nagra Hudson power merger in de\nfinance of the decisions reached by the\nlegal and accounting staff of the com\nmission.\nThe Boulder Dam situation is crit\nical, from the people\u2019s standpoint.\nCongress authorized the Secretary of\nthe Interior to determine whether\nthe dam on the Colorado River should\nbe equipped with its power plant by\nfederal or municipal government or\nprivate interests and whether the\npower should be allotted to one or\nto a variety of bidders. Hearings\nwere completed Nov. 13 on the pro\ntests which Los Angeles and other\nsouthern California cities made\nagainst Wilbur\u2019s determination to set\naside half of the power for pumping\nwater from the reservoir to the cities\nof southern California, and then to\ndivide evenly the remaining -power\nbetween the city of Low-Angeles and\nthe Southern California Edison Co.,\nLos Angeles and her si^er cities\nshowed that Los Angele^ ought to be\ngiven all this surplus- -power\u2014above\nthe amount necessary to pump their\nwater supply across the mountains\nand that Los Angeles would then dis\ntribute it more cheaply to other cities\nand to her own people than the pri\nvate company would. They insisted\nthat Wilbur obey the clause in the act\nwhich gives preference to municipal\nities.\nAgainst this argument the South\nern California Edison Co., backed by\nhalf a dozen other branches of the\npower trust, filed a demand for still\nmore of the power than Wilbur has\nallotted to it. The power trust urged\nthat Wilbur could not intend to en-\nBoy\u2019s Overcoat\nSpecial\nSizes\u2014Age 3 to 14\nPrice Range Regular\n$r.95 $y.95 $0.95\n$11.95 SJQ.9S\nand up\nAll This Fall\u2019s Styles, Latest\nPatterns and Models\n20% Discount\nOn whole stock of boy\u2019s overcoats\nSchacht -Erickson, Inc.\ncourage public ownership.\n\u201cCertainly,\u201d its petition said, \u201cyou\nhave no desire to use a great federal\nproject financed by public funds in\nsuch a manner as to stimulate the\ngrowth of the public ownership in\nsouthern California.\nThis crisis in the relations of Sec\nretary Wilbur to the power tru^ on\nthe one hand and the people on the\nother needs sharp watching during\nthe period of business slump. White\nHouse hints that, somehow, ther^ w\u2019ill\nbe better employment if private com\npanies build the power plants than\nif public authorities build them, have\nno grounding in fact. Yet under cover\nof public anxiety to avoid greater\nunemployment\u2014a crisis largely due\nto the speculation in watered stocks\nof the power trust itself\u2014the power\ntrust may grab hundreds of millions\nof dollars\u2019 worth of public assets.\nSCOTCH JOKES AGAIN\nAn exchange has garnered some of\nthe scotch gags that have been cir\nculated for the past twn years and\nhas compiled them as follows:\n\u201cHave you heard of the Scotchman\nwho\u2014\n\u2014Would give a thousand dollars to\nbe a millionaire?\n\n\u2014Went crazy because he bought a\nscore card at a ball game and neither\nside scored?\n\n\u2014Stood on the street corner with\ntwo slices of bread in his hand wait\ning for the traffic jam?\n\n\u2014Talked through his nose to save\nhis false teeth?\n\n\u2014Went coocoo trying to shoot off\na cannon a little at a time?\n\u2014Took his girl to a restaurant be\ncause he had always heard that it\nwas the woman who pa\\s\n\n\u2014Asked the floor walker in a five\nand ten cent store where the furni\nture department was\n\n\u2014Cured his sickness by swallowing\na quarter\n\n\u2014Wrote a farewell note and then\nwent to a neighbor\u2019s house and tum\ned on the gas?\n\u2014Works his crossword puzzle up\nI and down because he doesn\u2019t want\nto come across\n\n\u2014Gave his friends two homing pig\neons as a birthday present\n\u2014Who grew a wart on the back of\n1 his neck to serve as a collar button\n\n\u2014Hoarded all his toys for his sec\nond childhood\n\n\u2014Couldn\u2019t advertise because he\ncouldn\u2019t find an ad small enough\nPatronize our advertisers \u2014and tell\nthem why!","height":"27615","width":"20472"}}
